## 📌 Architectural Context: Telemetry Render Engine
The BDA Municipal Monitoring Center processes thousands of concurrent events from Edge IoT devices (Weighbridges, Smart POS). Directly mutating the DOM for every incoming packet causes catastrophic layout thrashing. 

We deployed a **Component-Based Architecture (React 18+)** utilizing the React Fiber engine. This acts as an abstraction layer, batching state updates and running heuristic `O(n)` reconciliation algorithms to only re-render the exact UI nodes that mutated.

### ⚙️ State Orchestration & Reconciliation Flow

```text
 [IoT Stream] ──► [Custom Hook: useTelemetry] ──► [Global State Manager]
                                                           │
       ┌───────────────────────┬───────────────────────────┤ (Unidirectional Props)
       ▼                       ▼                           ▼
 [Memoized Node]         [Memoized Node]             [Memoized Node]
 (Smart POS 1)           (Weighbridge A)             (Weighbridge B)
       │                       │                           │
       └───────────────► [VIRTUAL DOM RECONCILIATION] ◄────┘
                                   │
                                   ▼
                       [SELECTIVE BROWSER PAINT]





🏗️ Engineering Focus: Advanced Reactivity
Custom Hooks (useTelemetryStream): Encapsulating complex network logic (simulating WebSockets) outside of the UI components to maintain strict separation of concerns.

Memoization (React.memo): Wrapping leaf-nodes in memoization wrappers. If a weighbridge's data hasn't changed, React skips its render phase entirely, saving immense CPU cycles during data floods.

Immutability: Guaranteeing that state is never mutated directly, ensuring the React Fiber engine can perform high-speed strict equality checks (===).

